      </div>

      <p class="body-text" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
        <strong>Edson Pavoni</strong> is a Brazilian artist whose journey began in the streets of São Paulo, where a context of poverty and violence shaped his early years. In a country where Christianity offered a path away from the streets, drugs, and violence, Pavoni found refuge in faith, a theme that would later when he became a critic of religion abuses informed his artistic practice.
      </p>
      <p class="body-text">
        In 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic, Pavoni created <strong><a href="https://inumeraveis.com.br/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: none; transition: text-decoration 0.2s;" onmouseover="this.style.textDecoration='underline'" onmouseout="this.style.textDecoration='none'">Inumeráveis (innumerable)</a></strong>, an artwork at the intersection of art and journalism. The project interviewed thousands of families, and wrote stories of those lost to the pandemic, creating a space where memory transcended numbers and statistics. Poems, songs, and symphonies were made with those stories. Newspapers created covers using the names and histories. Brazilian stars read those stories on national television. The project reached 32 million people, one in four Brazilian adults. It became a network of healing, a collective monument to memory.
      </p>
      <p class="body-text">
        The media used those stories every week, and Pavoni was on TV almost every week for a year. All because no one wants to be a number. Everyone deserves to exist in prose. After more than ten thousand conversations with grief, a pattern emerged: when we talk about someone who has died, we select fragments of their story as if writing a letter of recommendation to the gatekeeper of paradise. We do our best to send them to what we believe is heaven.
      </p>
      <p class="body-text">
        This work sparked a deeper inquiry: why should who is remembered after death follow the same logic of meritocracy that governs life? Orbital Temple emerges from this question. Temples, Pavoni believes, unlock the creative power of our deepest unconscious selves, spaces where we can imagine radically different ways of being together.
      </p>
      <p class="body-text">
        He lives and works in New York.
      </p>

      <h3 class="subsection-heading">
